INFLUENZA, PANDEMIC: DISEASE ARCHEOLOGY (2)
===========================================
See Also
Influenza, pandemic: disease archeology archive.960530
Date: Tue. 4 June 1996
At 06:44 PM 5/30/96 MDT, Charles H Calisher <ccalisher@vines.colostate.edu>
wrote:
>Attempts to isolate viruses from frozen corpses found in Siberia, Alaska or
>other very cold places have been made many times. I know of no successes.
>The Canadians who are planning to exhume frozen Norwegian corpses might have
>an adventure in store for themselves but it is not likely they will isolate an
>influenza virus from such tissues. PCR might be a better tool, or at least an
>adjunct tool, for such work.
>TB, nephropathia epidemica, rabies, ennui, and many other etiologies in
addition to influenza might have been responsible for the deaths of those
people.
>
>I hope this work is tax deductible or at least that CME credit will be given.
[I'd give them the benefit of the doubt. I assume they've established that
the 7 people died in the winter of 1918-19, during the pandemic, and that
there are records that the pandemic actually reached the island where they
are buried. Otherwise I very much doubt they'd be funded - Mod.JW
>Date: Fri, 31 May 1996 09:33:06 -0400 (EDT)
>From: Paul Millikin <U21900@UICVM.CC.UIC.EDU>
>
>I studied pathology under Milton C. Winternitz, noted educator and former
>Dean of Yale. As a young pathologist, he did a lot of work on that flu
>epidemic, and as I recall, he told us that a lot of the damage was caused
>by beta hemolytic streptococci. After all these years, I don't quote that
>as gospel, but I hope the current investigators will look at bacteria, too.
............................................................................JW

